<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06027075 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06027075 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Bush; PHOTO: Gephardt  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  CONGRESS; LEGISLATION; ETHICS; PROBE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Congress, its attention diverted by the war in the Persian Gulf, must stillconfront the federal deficit, the savings and loan crisis and its own ethicsproblems.;    These and a host of other issues, including confirmation of Bushadministration Cabinet nominees, await action when the first session of the102nd Congress swings into high gear this week.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  DEFICIT, Sandamp;L CRISIS AND ETHICS ISSUES CONFRONTCONGRESS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Although lawmakers have spent considerable time discussing the war, thelegislative agenda has not been thrown askew; the House and Senatetraditionally await the State of the Union message before getting down to thebusiness of writing laws.;    Bush to focus on gulf war;  President Bush willfocus heavily on the war when he delivers his assessment of America's healthto a joint session of Congress and to a national broadcast audience Tuesdaynight.;    The following week, the president sends his proposed budget for thefiscal year that begins Oct. 1 to Congress in an atmosphere of uncertaintyover the war's costs and the recession at home. The plan is expected to callfor more than $1.2 trillion in spending and to carry a record deficitexceeding $300 billion.;    Cabinet nominations;  The Senate, among otherthings, must decide whether to confirm the nominations of Lynn Martin assecretary of labor, Edward Madigan as agriculture secretary and Bob Martinezas national drug control director.;    Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,D-Maine, has cited national health care as a high priority for congressionalDemocrats, and the Bush administration is likely to try again to getlegislation enacted that imposes the death penalty for a host of categories offederal crimes.;    &quot;We are not going to screech everything to a halt in termsof our domestic agenda,&quot; Bush told reporters at a White House news conferenceFriday.;     On the war, he said he couldn't supply specific figures on likelycosts, although Bush did say he hoped to have more such information thisweek.;    War cost estimate;  Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Monterey, chairman of theHouse Budget Committee, has said he believes fighting in the gulf could costthe United States $500 million to $750 million daily.;    The price tag forthe war is estimated to be anywhere between $28 billion and $86 billion,according to recent figures from the Congressional Budget Office.;   Lawmakers will consider a supplemental spending bill to cover the cost ofOperation Desert Storm late next month or in early March.;    Likely scenario; Because of the five-year budget agreement Bush and congressional leadersreached last fall, many decisions about broad spending limits and taxincreases have already been made.;    Instead, lawmakers and the Bushadministration will probably spend time this year battling over whether toraise taxes to pay for the fighting -- as some Democrats have proposed -- andwhether to initiate new domestic programs to combat the recession.;    &quot;Thedirty little secret in Washington these days is that the Bush administrationhad no domestic agenda the day before Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait, and itwill have no domestic agenda the day after we drive Saddam Hussein out ofKuwait,&quot; said House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.;    Democrats forhome issues;  He said Democrats should push for education and technologyprograms to help Americans compete and to ensure &quot;that the strength andprosperity they are fighting for abroad is not squandered here at home.&quot;;   Other issues are:;    (check) The savings and loan crisis. Congress, whichadjourned last year without providing the money to keep the savings and loanbailout going, is being asked to provide another $30 billion to cover lossesin failed thrifts.;    (check) Reformation of federal campaign finance laws.Attempts last year to revise law to substantially limit the impact ofpolitical action committees on members of the House and Senate collapsed amidfights over public financing and other provisions.;    (check) Civil rightslegislation, long-term health care and a crime bill with a possible ban onassault weapons.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910127  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  655  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday January 27, 199100027075,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>